New programmers tend to worry too much about input and output.  I&#39;d recommend focusing on the function itself:

    /**
     * @link https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpao/growthcharts/training/bmiage/page5_2.html
     */
    public class BMICalculator {
    
        public static final double CONVERSION_POUNDS_AND_INCHES = 703.0;

        private final double conversion;

        public BMICalculator() { this(CONVERSION_POUNDS_AND_INCHES); }
    
        public BMICalculator(double conversion) { 
            this.conversion = conversion;
        }
    
        public double calculateIndex(double weight, double height) {
            return this.conversion*weight/height/height;
        }
    }

Learn [JUnit][1] and write good unit tests.  Prove that your function works, then move on to input and output.

What about negative weights and heights?  What should your function do if these are entered?  What about zero height?  What will your function do?  Write tests for each one.

You&#39;re a new developer.  One thing you might consider is the new JDK 8 functional interfaces.  You can use lambdas that way:

    public class BMICalculator implements ToDoubleBiFunction&lt;Double, Double&gt;{
    
        public static final double CONVERSION = 703.0;
    
        public double applyAsDouble(Double weightPounds, Double heightInches) {
            return CONVERSION*weightPounds/heightInches/heightInches;
        }
    }


